0%5D=started_experiment_milestone&origin=journalDetail',NULL,'\nAim: The study aims to apply clinical staging to young people who present for mental health care; to describe the demographic features, patterns of psychological symptoms, disability correlates and clinical stages of those young people; and to report longitudinal estimates of progression from less to more severe stages.\nMethods: The study uses crosssectional and longitudinal assessments of young people managed in specialized youth clinics. On the basis of clinical records, subjects were assigned to a specific clinical ├éΓÇÿstage├éΓÇÖ(ie ├éΓÇÿhelp-seeking├éΓÇÖ,├éΓÇÿattenuated syndrome├éΓÇÖ,├éΓÇÿdiscrete disorder├éΓÇÖor ├éΓÇÿpersistent or recurrent illness├éΓÇÖ).\nResults: Young people (n= 209, mean age= 19.9 years (range= 12├éΓÇô30 years), 48% female) were selected from a broader cohort of n= 1483 subjects. Ten percent were assigned to the earliest ├éΓÇÿhelp-seeking├éΓÇÖstage, 54% to the ├éΓÇÿattenuated syndrome├éΓÇÖstage, 25% to the ├éΓÇÿdiscrete disorder├éΓÇÖstage and 11% to the later ├éΓÇÿpersistent or recurrent illness├éΓÇÖ stage. The interrater reliability of independent ratings at baseline was acceptable (k= 0.71). Subjects assigned to the ├éΓÇÿattenuated syndrome├éΓÇÖstage reported symptom and disability scores that were similar to those assigned to later stages. Longitudinally (median= 48 weeks), transition to later clinical stages were 11% of the ├éΓÇÿhelp-seeking├éΓÇÖ, 19% of the ├éΓÇÿattenuated syndrome├éΓÇÖand 33% of the ├éΓÇÿdiscrete disorder├éΓÇÖgroups.\nConclusion: Among young people presenting for mental health care, most are clinically staged as having ├éΓÇÿattenuated syndromes├éΓÇÖ. Despite access to specialized treatment, a significant number progress to more severe or persistent disorders.\n','',2016,NULL,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','','','','',NULL,NULL,NULL),(1579,'O-10-Safety monitoring guidelines for treatments for major depressive disorder','https://www.cambridge